Jun 26 2007 	Solid value but some limitations	Overall this place has maximized what it can do with what it is. It looks like it used to be a rundown roadside motel, and they completely refurbished the place and renovated the rooms with cute trendy decor, and lots of nice modern amenities like digital cable TV, fridge, microwave, free wireless internet. There is a modest free continental breakfast (i.e. donuts and sandwiches from Dunkin Donuts, juice, coffee) and free internet in the lobby. The manager was extremely polite and helpful upon check-in and gave a list of local restaurants and suggestions. There is a free shuttle to/from the airport available. The Orange Line subway is only a couple blocks away and takes you right to the Loop downtown (and the airport). The location is ok, a quiet commercial suburban area that seems lower middle class and fairly safe. There is a mini-mall nearby with groceries and restaurants, including the local favorite pizza chain Giordano's. The only problem is the facilities themselves, which are limited by their construction and by budget. The biggest thing that bothered me was that the room had a musty, somewhat mildewy odor, probably because the rooms have local climate control and are close to the elements (the hallways are open to the outdoors). There were minor glitches in the renovation (the door was a little too big and ran into the toilet in the bathroom each time you opened the door, the tub faucet looked like it was going to pop out of the wall, etc.) The hair dryer was weak, the towels were small and not very soft (although surprisingly absorbent) and the sheets were kind of scratchy (although the bed itself was quite comfortable). The place was clean. An open motel tends to be noisier, and you could hear people coming in the middle of the night and talking loudly outside, although airport and street noise was minimal at night.Overall though I think this is a worthwhile place that has tried their hardest to maximize what they could with what they have, with a solid management, and it is convenient. Just realize that the facilities will have some limitations.	
Apr 26 2007 	A good choice in hotels	Went to Chicago to visit colleges with my son. We stayed two nights in double beds for the AAA price of about $112/night. I was wary of this hotel because it only had two diamonds from AAA and I had stayed downtown at another two diamond hotel which was not very comfortable. I was pleasantly surprised.The lobby staff were very friendly, giving helpful advice on where to eat and how to use the 'el train'. The rooms had been remodeled just four years ago and were up to date and very clean. The beds and pillows were very comfortable. An in-room refrigerator, microwave and free broadband internet access makes this a top choice for my future visits. You don't get that at any of the other much more expensive hotels that offer &quot;premium service&quot;.A grocery store, and all kinds of familiar foods are within two or three blocks walking distance but most offer free delivery to the hotel. The El train is only one block away getting you downtown with ease in less than 25-minutes but it's also an easy trip back to the I-55 highway. A couple of channels on the TV were fuzzy and I brought it to their attention. I was in a room toward the back and wasn't affected by the busy street noise, though I could hear a couple of &quot;big rigs&quot; during the day. Overhead airplane noise from Midway was noticeable until about 11pm or so but not overnight. Apparently traffic patterns change, too, and the second night I heard none. I deducted one star for this but it did not keep me from getting a good nights sleep.The neighborhood is busy with traffic and I felt somewhat uncomfortable walking it at first, but I then realized my fears were unfounded and I think it's perfectly safe. Asking directions and questions a few times of the locals brought friendly responses.Free coffee, doughnuts and, especially, breakfast sandwiches were another pleasant surprise. My last two stays in Chicago were at the high-end Palmer House downtown. The services offered and available at this Carlton Inn give me no reason to do that anymore.	
